ce:section.ce:para:
The quenching effect to the fluorescence intensity of NFCDs when solutions had different ClO− concentrations was investigated in order to calculate the limit of detection (LOD) and the detection range, as shown in Fig. 6
                     . The overlapped fluorescence spectra of the NFCDs dispersed solutions containing varied concentrations of ClO− is presented in Fig. 6a. It was found that the fluorescence intensity of the mixture decreased gradually as the ClO− concentration increased. Fig. 6b presents a plot of the fluorescence intensity versus the ClO− concentration; there is a strong linear correlation (R2 = 0.9958) between the intensity and the ClO− concentration in the range of 0–20 μM ClO− (inset of Fig. 6a). Based on the "three times the standard deviation" rule, the LOD value was calculated as ~12.0 nM. Compared with other carbon dots probes reported previously, the NFCDs probe demonstrated lower LOD and wider range for ClO− detection (see Table 1
                     ) [46–53]. These results indicate the promising potential of NFCDs in real water applications. The quench mechanism of NFCDs by ClO− ions were investigated via measuring their lifetimes, as shown in Fig. 6c and 6d. For the NFCDs, time-resolved PL measurements revealed mono-exponential decay trace with lifetimes of 4.2 ns. After quenched by ClO− ions, the PL decay curves were fitted by dual exponential decay traces with two lifetimes and the average lifetimes (τavg.) of quenched NFCDs were reduced gradually as increasing the concentration of ClO− ions. When ClO− ions were added in the NFCDs solution, their strong oxidation should destroy the surface of NFCDs and enhance the nonradiative carrier depopulation, further leading to shorten fluorescence lifetime (τ1) and weakened fluorescence intensity. Meantime, the surface composition of the oxidized NFCDs were changed due to the incorporation of Cl or O elements and new excited carriers were generated, whose lifetime (τ2) were increased gradually with increased ClO− concentration. Of course, the contribution of τ2 to the average lifetime of NFCDs was negligible because their proportion was always lower than 0.1%, much less than the τ1.
